&gt;&gt; Start over here on the left.

00:23:48.450 --> 00:23:52.850
&gt;&gt; Yes. I'd like your response to
the conundrum and the controversy

00:23:53.190 --> 00:23:56.723
about the collapse of three,
not two, but three towers

00:23:56.940 --> 00:24:00.806
at the eastern end of Manhattan
eleven years ago this month

00:24:02.240 --> 00:24:05.573
as if they were the products
of planned demolition.

00:24:06.710 --> 00:24:06.860
Not only were these two towers --

00:24:08.760 --> 00:24:10.066
two of these towers struck
by airplanes, in addition,

00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:15.720
at least one other, another building
as tall as either of the twin towers

00:24:15.770 --> 00:24:18.636
in this planet and
damaged as much as either

00:24:19.450 --> 00:24:23.450
of the twin towers withstood
the shock and remained standing.

00:24:23.580 --> 00:24:27.180
What are civil engineers
saying about this controversy?

00:24:29.150 --> 00:24:29.806
&gt;&gt; You're talking about
I believe what is known

00:24:31.560 --> 00:24:31.590
as World Trade Center Seven, a
building that was hit by some debris

00:24:35.930 --> 00:24:39.796
and caught on fire and burned
essentially almost overnight,

00:24:40.350 --> 00:24:43.016
as I recall, and eventually
did collapse.

00:24:43.670 --> 00:24:48.203
The fact of the matter is that there
was so much attention being paid

00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:53.613
to the World Trade Center towers
proper, World Trade Center Tower one

00:24:54.160 --> 00:24:58.560
and two, which were much taller
than that World Trade Center seven,

00:24:59.150 --> 00:25:02.950
by a factor of roughly two,
that that was not a big issue,

00:25:04.100 --> 00:25:06.966
because people had been
evacuated from that.

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:09.640
And there was just
not the same concern.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:13.333
But there are conspiracy
theories about the fall --

00:25:15.230 --> 00:25:17.496
about the -- what did you call it?

00:25:18.120 --> 00:25:19.586
Controlled demolition.

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:21.340
&gt;&gt; Yes

00:25:22.340 --> 00:25:23.750
&gt;&gt; I think generally civil
engineers, structural engineers

00:25:24.730 --> 00:25:28.596
in particular don't subscribe
to those conspiracy theories.

00:25:29.830 --> 00:25:32.030
They believe, generally speaking,

00:25:32.790 --> 00:25:36.656
that all three towers collapsed
largely due to two factors.

00:25:39.320 --> 00:25:41.653
One was that by the planes striking

00:25:42.150 --> 00:25:44.750
or the debris striking
these structures,

00:25:45.030 --> 00:25:48.563
certain key structural
elements were damaged, columns.

00:25:48.640 --> 00:25:49.226
If you take one of these poles
out from under this tent,

00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:52.086
you don't expect the
tent to be as strong

00:25:54.020 --> 00:25:56.086
as it is with all of its poles.

00:25:56.780 --> 00:25:59.380
And that, secondly,
as the fires burned,

00:25:59.470 --> 00:26:01.470
they naturally generated heat.

00:26:01.470 --> 00:26:02.313
And the heat, if you heat
up these columns here,

00:26:03.760 --> 00:26:07.093
they appear to be metal,
they're going to get soft.

00:26:08.210 --> 00:26:09.236
And they're just not
going to have the strength

00:26:10.250 --> 00:26:12.050
that they were intended to.

00:26:12.710 --> 00:26:12.946
So as a result, eventually
this structure will collapse.

00:26:16.140 --> 00:26:19.806
There are reasonable structural
engineering explanations

00:26:20.210 --> 00:26:21.543
for those collapses.

00:26:24.200 --> 00:26:25.200
Yes, sir?

00:26:26.200 --> 00:26:27.896
&gt;&gt; As somebody who had his education
and career in engineering physics,

00:26:29.170 --> 00:26:32.970
I'd be very interested in your
comments on the convergence

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:37.386
as we get into the nano region
of both theoretical physics,

00:26:39.810 --> 00:26:40.173
theoretical -- let's
say theoretical science,

00:26:42.380 --> 00:26:44.780
experimental science
and engineering.

00:26:44.950 --> 00:26:47.883
They seem to be coming
together in this ring.

00:26:47.910 --> 00:26:49.376
&gt;&gt; Well, that's right.

00:26:49.910 --> 00:26:50.270
In order to produce especially
some of the electronic devices

00:26:53.550 --> 00:26:56.150
and components that
are being projected,

00:26:56.370 --> 00:26:58.636
you have to know a lot of physics.

00:27:00.040 --> 00:27:00.156
And as I think it's a gosh example

00:27:02.190 --> 00:27:02.240
of what I was saying is there
has to be close interaction.

00:27:05.940 --> 00:27:10.406
I will say that it's hard to predict
what's going to happen or going

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:14.520
to be the limitations,
because almost

00:27:15.340 --> 00:27:15.670
by definition we don't know what
they are, because we don't know

00:27:19.210 --> 00:27:22.210
as much about the science
as we really should.

00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:24.493
There's still open questions.

00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:27.680
Yes, sir?

00:27:28.680 --> 00:27:30.546
&gt;&gt; Yes. The previous two
speakers in this tent were dealing

00:27:30.680 --> 00:27:34.880
with different issues, be it farm
produced poultry and products.

00:27:36.400 --> 00:27:38.600
Edmund O. Wilson was here before.

00:27:39.300 --> 00:27:41.633
I think the key to bridging science

00:27:42.880 --> 00:27:46.813
and solutions is human factors
engineering and the expansion

00:27:47.140 --> 00:27:49.073
of human factors engineering.

00:27:49.140 --> 00:27:49.273
I haven't heard you speak on it.

00:27:51.140 --> 00:27:51.406
Would you have an opinion on that?

00:27:53.140 --> 00:27:53.473
&gt;&gt; Well, I didn't mention it today.

00:27:55.140 --> 00:27:56.140
I have talked about human
factors engineering,

00:27:57.140 --> 00:27:58.593
but human factors engineering
has various definitions.

00:27:59.220 --> 00:27:59.330
To some people it means
simply making machines

00:28:02.110 --> 00:28:05.710
that people can interact
with, that humans can interact

00:28:06.340 --> 00:28:08.873
with without ambiguity
and with safety.

00:28:10.250 --> 00:28:13.583
I think there are some
attempts to broaden the idea

00:28:13.700 --> 00:28:13.900
of what human factors
engineering means.

00:28:16.100 --> 00:28:18.566
And I think that's
a good development.

00:28:19.660 --> 00:28:19.986
It's hard to be against
something like that.

00:28:22.200 --> 00:28:26.733
And, well, I think it bodes well
for the objectives that we all have.

00:28:29.030 --> 00:28:30.030
Yes, sir?

00:28:31.030 --> 00:28:35.563
&gt;&gt; Given the failures of this decade
ending in 2010, what do you feel

00:28:36.430 --> 00:28:39.630
about universities'
professors teaching engineers

00:28:40.520 --> 00:28:44.253
for the global warming changes,
things that have come up?

00:28:44.330 --> 00:28:44.596
Any challenges for the next decade

00:28:46.330 --> 00:28:48.930
so that we maybe don't
have Katrina two,

00:28:49.500 --> 00:28:51.900
gulf spill two, those
type of things?

00:28:52.830 --> 00:28:53.210
Do you think we're prepared
enough going forward?

00:28:55.650 --> 00:28:55.666
&gt;&gt; Well, you know,
Katrina sensitized people

00:28:58.500 --> 00:29:00.233
to the weakness of levies.

00:29:00.640 --> 00:29:02.080
And not only to the weakness of
levies, but also to the weakness

00:29:03.400 --> 00:29:07.733
to the entire system that was
supposed to help New Orleans respond

00:29:09.350 --> 00:29:11.216
to something of that nature.

00:29:11.390 --> 00:29:11.416
The gulf spill, the recent gulf
spill has sensitized people

00:29:15.230 --> 00:29:17.630
to deep water drilling and so forth.

00:29:17.650 --> 00:29:22.050
So these failures will have an
immediate effect of making engineers

00:29:22.800 --> 00:29:26.733
and people that commission
engineers a little more cautious,

00:29:27.060 --> 00:29:28.860
a little more conservative.

00:29:29.060 --> 00:29:30.043
So I would predict, if you're asking
me to predict, over the next decade

00:29:32.810 --> 00:29:32.956
that we're not going to see
another Katrina in New Orleans.

00:29:36.530 --> 00:29:37.076
We may see another Katrina
elsewhere, because so many

00:29:39.450 --> 00:29:43.450
of the resources that it would
take to bring levies elsewhere

00:29:44.390 --> 00:29:47.256
up to speed are really
going to New Orleans.

00:29:48.250 --> 00:29:48.716
And there's just a
limit to, you know,

00:29:50.250 --> 00:29:50.316
how many resources we can have.

00:29:52.250 --> 00:29:52.306
The Netherlands, which has had
historically a levy problem,

00:29:56.060 --> 00:29:59.060
if you will, is thinking
in terms of 200 years

00:30:00.780 --> 00:30:02.846
and in some cases a millennium.

00:30:02.860 --> 00:30:07.126
They are very long range thinking
and action on a national scale.

00:30:08.660 --> 00:30:11.060
We haven't gotten to that point yet.

00:30:11.180 --> 00:30:15.646
So I think we really have to look
elsewhere for some further lessons

00:30:18.050 --> 00:30:20.783
about what we can do
to prevent disasters.

00:30:22.720 --> 00:30:23.720
Yes?

00:30:24.720 --> 00:30:25.116
&gt;&gt; Professor, you wrote a
book 11 or 12 years ago,

00:30:27.590 --> 00:30:29.323
The Book on the Bookshelf.

00:30:29.590 --> 00:30:30.590
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:30:31.590 --> 00:30:33.990
&gt;&gt; And in that you discuss many of
the things you brought up today,

00:30:33.590 --> 00:30:36.256
invention, innovation,
the profit motive.

00:30:37.010 --> 00:30:41.476
And in that context I wonder if you
would just address the evolution

00:30:42.130 --> 00:30:46.196
in publishing today of E-Books
and P-Books [assumed spelling].

00:30:46.260 --> 00:30:47.393
&gt;&gt; I wish I knew.

00:30:49.300 --> 00:30:53.033
There is so much being reported
and written on that topic

00:30:54.050 --> 00:30:58.050
that I will admit to being
bewildered about what's happening.

00:31:00.840 --> 00:31:03.573
I think E-Books are a
natural development.

00:31:05.100 --> 00:31:09.100
Whether they will actually
displace the physical book or not,

00:31:09.130 --> 00:31:11.330
I think remains an open question.

00:31:11.560 --> 00:31:11.843
And I think the publishers play more
of a role in this than they seem

00:31:15.810 --> 00:31:18.610
to have admitted or
seem to be acting upon.

00:31:19.260 --> 00:31:23.126
I think the publishers in a
certain way are silent partners

00:31:23.920 --> 00:31:25.586
to the E-Book revolution.

00:31:26.140 --> 00:31:30.673
It's a lot easier to produce and
more profitable to produce an E-Book

00:31:30.930 --> 00:31:30.976
than it is a regular printed book.

00:31:33.150 --> 00:31:37.550
I wish we would see more innovation,
innovated thinking on the part

00:31:39.090 --> 00:31:39.380
of publishers with
regard to E-Books.

00:31:41.200 --> 00:31:43.400
And I simply haven't seen it yet.

00:31:43.780 --> 00:31:44.430
So I think that's going
to be the next wave

00:31:45.930 --> 00:31:47.730
if the publishers are going

00:31:47.930 --> 00:31:51.396
to really fight what they
claim they'd like to fight.

00:31:52.620 --> 00:31:56.620
They're largely fighting it on
the basis of money and profit,

00:31:57.210 --> 00:32:00.143
but not in terms of
technology in my opinion.

00:32:00.520 --> 00:32:01.520
Yes, sir?

00:32:02.520 --> 00:32:04.353
&gt;&gt; Yes. Professor, a lot of people
here don't realize that you're one

00:32:05.220 --> 00:32:09.620
of the experts on failure analysis
and that you teach that at Duke.

00:32:10.660 --> 00:32:13.060
And my question is,
the current modes

00:32:15.860 --> 00:32:20.460
of failure analysis we see now, that
is, the software failures that is

00:32:21.070 --> 00:32:25.336
like the 1990 national telephone
failure, I would say that is not

00:32:25.810 --> 00:32:28.410
so much between science
and engineering,

00:32:30.700 --> 00:32:31.020
but a failure between high level
engineering or systems engineering

00:32:34.780 --> 00:32:36.446
and detailed engineering.

00:32:36.780 --> 00:32:37.053
Essentially that failure was
because they wanted to save money,

00:32:40.640 --> 00:32:41.440
they took the system engineering
specs and they brought it

00:32:43.640 --> 00:32:47.706
into code instead of letting the
